  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can tax exemption be availed on tax saving FD for the entire tenure of 5 years by investing 1.5 lakhs in the 1st year?",
  "response": "In India, tax-saving fixed deposits (FDs) are a popular investment option under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act, which allows for tax deductions. Here are some key points to consider regarding tax exemptions on tax-saving FDs:\n\n1. **Investment Limit**: The maximum amount that can be invested in tax-saving FDs to avail tax benefits under Section 80C is \u20b91.5 lakh per financial year.\n\n2. **Lock-in Period**: Tax-saving FDs have a lock-in period of 5 years. You cannot withdraw the amount before the completion of this period.\n\n3. **Tax Deduction**: The amount invested in tax-saving FDs can be claimed as a deduction from your taxable income in the year of investment, subject to the overall limit of \u20b91.5 lakh under Section 80C.\n\n4. **Tax on Interest**: The interest earned on tax-saving FDs is taxable. Banks deduct TDS (Tax Deducted at Source) on the interest if it exceeds \u20b940,000 in a financial year (\u20b950,000 for senior citizens). The TDS rate is 10% if your PAN is linked to the FD account.\n\n5. **Exemption on Principal**: The principal amount invested in the tax-saving FD is exempt from tax at the time of maturity. However, this exemption is not spread over the tenure of the FD but is applicable only at the time of investment.\n\nGiven these points, if you invest \u20b91.5 lakh in a tax-saving FD in the first year, you can claim a deduction of up to \u20b91.5 lakh under Section 80C for that financial year. However, the tax exemption applies only to the principal amount at the time of investment and not over the entire tenure of the FD. The interest earned will be taxable annually.\n\nTo summarize, the tax exemption on the principal amount of \u20b91.5 lakh is availed in the first year of investment, not over the entire 5-year tenure. The interest earned each year will be subject to tax.",
